\newpage 
# Health Inequality Analysis   
## Principles

## Demonstration
### Functions Related to Health Inequality Analysis  
```{r eval=FALSE}
# For configuring Stata path
config_stata()
# Modeling
GBDslope_index()
GBDconcentration_index()
GBDconcentration_compare()
#Visualize model results
ggslope_index()
ggconcentration_index()
```

### First-time Use of GBDconcentration_index Requires Configuring Stata Path
```{r eval=FALSE}
## Note!!: Stata cannot be installed on the system disk, otherwise R cannot call Stata
# path: folder path where exe or mac executable program is located
# version: Stata version number
# stata_type: Stata type
config_stata(path, version = 15, stata_type = c("SE", "MP", "IC"))

```

### Calculate Slope Index and Plot
```{r eval=FALSE}
# Data reading
data <- read.csv("all causes.csv",header = T)

# Calculate slope index
## Must have 204 countries
## all_age_range: If it is original data downloaded from the GBD website, set all_age_range to NULL. If it is data for partial age groups calculated through GBDage_recal/GBDrei_age_recal, please provide the upper and lower limits of the age group, ensuring that the values in all_age_range are the lower limit values in a 5-year age structure. For example, for a 20-49 year old population, set your all_age_range to c(20,45)
res <- GBDslope_index(data, ## Original GBD data
                      all_age_range=NULL, ##This parameter is mainly used to calculate the slope index for specific age structures
                      SDI=T, ##Whether to calculate the slope index for 5 SDI regions
                      GBDregion=T, ##Whether to calculate the slope index for 19 GBD regions
                      SuperGBDregion=T) ##Whether to calculate the slope index for 7 SuperGBD regions

# Slope index plotting
ggslope_index(data=res,
              model='rlm', ##Model selection, can choose lm or rlm based on ncvTest_p results
              color_name=c("#6699FF","#990000"), ##Color selection
              group_name='year', ## Grouping variable for comparing two groups
              region_name='All included', ##Filter variable
              measure_name='DALYs (Disability-Adjusted Life Years)', ##Filter variable
              sex_name='Both', ##Filter variable
              cause_name='All causes', ##Filter variable
              rei_name=NULL, ##Filter variable
              age_name='All ages', ##Filter variable
              year_name=c(1990,2019), ##Filter variable
              country_label='China', ##Label country names in the figure
              population_count=10e6) ##Population label
```

In the figure below, the main results are in the slope dataset, including two results: lm (ordinary linear model) and rlm (robust linear model). The results of the two models mainly refer to the heteroscedasticity test (ncvTest_p). If the test result P-value is less than 0.05, there is heteroscedasticity, consider using the rlm (robust linear model) result; if the test result P-value is greater than 0.05, there is no heteroscedasticity, consider using the lm (ordinary linear model) result.
![](D:/BaiduSyncdisk/2.课题/easy GBDR写作/easyGBDRdocument/GBDslope_index.png)
The figure below shows the results of the slope index
![](D:/BaiduSyncdisk/2.课题/easy GBDR写作/easyGBDRdocument/ggslope_index.png)


### Calculate Concentration Index and Plot (Requires Calling Stata Function)
```{r eval=FALSE}
# Data reading
data <- read.csv("all causes.csv",header = T)

# Calculate concentration index
## Must have 204 countries
## all_age_range: If it is original data downloaded from the GBD website, set all_age_range to NULL. If it is data for partial age groups calculated through GBDage_recal/GBDrei_age_recal, please provide the upper and lower limits of the age group, ensuring that the values in all_age_range are the lower limit values in a 5-year age structure. For example, for a 20-49 year old population, set your all_age_range to c(20,45)
res <- GBDconcentration_index(data, ## Original GBD data
                      all_age_range=NULL, ##This parameter is mainly used to calculate the slope index for specific age structures
                      SDI=T, ##Whether to calculate the slope index for 5 SDI regions
                      GBDregion=T, ##Whether to calculate the slope index for 19 GBD regions
                      SuperGBDregion=T) ##Whether to calculate the slope index for 7 SuperGBD regions

# Concentration index plotting
ggconcentration_index(data=res,
              color_name=c("#6699FF","#990000"), ##Color selection
              group_name='year', ## Grouping variable for comparing two groups
              region_name='All included', ##Filter variable
              measure_name='DALYs (Disability-Adjusted Life Years)', ##Filter variable
              sex_name='Both', ##Filter variable
              cause_name='All causes', ##Filter variable
              rei_name=NULL, ##Filter variable
              age_name='All ages', ##Filter variable
              year_name=c(1990,2019), ##Filter variable
              country_label=c('China','India'),##Label country names in the figure
              population_count=10e6) ##Population label

#Concentration index comparison
res_comprare <- GBDconcentration_compare(data=res, # Results of running GBDconcentration_index
                         group_name='year',  ## Grouping variable for comparing two groups
                         region_name='All included', ##Filter variable
                         measure_name='DALYs (Disability-Adjusted Life Years)', ##Filter variable
                         sex_name='Both', ##Filter variable
                         cause_name='All causes', ##Filter variable
                         rei_name=NULL, ##Filter variable
                         age_name='All ages', ##Filter variable
                         year_name=c(1990,2019)) ##Filter variable
```


The figure below shows the calculation results of the concentration index, with corresponding concentration index, SE, upper and lower limits, and corresponding P-values
![](D:/BaiduSyncdisk/2.课题/easy GBDR写作/easyGBDRdocument/concentration_index.png)

The figure below shows the results of the concentration index
![](D:/BaiduSyncdisk/2.课题/easy GBDR写作/easyGBDRdocument/ggconcentrtion_index.png)

The figure below shows the comparison results of two concentration indices, with two hypothesis test results, one indicating that the variances of the two groups are the same, and the other assuming that the sample sizes of the two groups are large. The results will also be stored in the form of a data frame
![](D:/BaiduSyncdisk/2.课题/easy GBDR写作/easyGBDRdocument/concentration_compare.png)

\newpage 
# QCI Calculation and Display
## Principles
  The principle of QCI is to use various indicators of a disease to calculate the ratio of Incidence to deaths, the ratio of YLD to YLL, the ratio of Prevalence to DALY, and the ratio of Incidence to Prevalence. Through the PCA method, the above indicators are included to calculate a PCA index, and then the QCI result is obtained. For specific principles, please refer to this literature **A global, regional, and national survey on burden and Quality of Care Index (QCI) of brain and other central nervous system cancers; global burden of disease systematic analysis 1990-2017**

## Demonstration
### Functions Related to QCI Calculation  
```{r eval=FALSE}
# Calculate QCI index
GBDqci_cal()
```


```{r eval=FALSE}
# Data reading
data <- readRDS(file = 'QCI_data.rds') %>% filter(metric == 'Rate') %>% unique()
## QCI calculation
res <- GBDqci_cal(data)
```



The figure below shows the results after running QCI: MIR is the ratio of Incidence to deaths, YLLtoYLD is the ratio of YLD to YLL, DALtoPER is the ratio of Prevalence to DALY, PERtoINC is the ratio of Incidence to Prevalence. QCI is the final calculated result, and QCI_component is the combination of the basis for QCI calculation
![](D:/BaiduSyncdisk/2.课题/easy GBDR写作/easyGBDRdocument/QCI.png)

